Comments: Limbs screwed off trees, express train sound. Tornado at Topar (E of Broken Hill) and possibly at Eldee (NW of Broken Hill) damaged trees and a garden shed.

Information passed on from Mike Bergen who spoke to the man who witnessed the funnel cloud while travelling on a bus to Wagga. The cell was about 15-20 km south of the coach. The cell was large, solitary and funnel cloud was distinct. The tornado was not observed to have touched-down". Tornado seen from bus by ex met observer on route to Wagga"

VERY NARROW AND TALL, FAIRLY STRAIGHT FROM GROUND TO CLOUD LEVEL. OBSERVED HALFWAY BETWEEN MACQUARIE CENTRE AND BLUE MTS.  NO DAMAGE OBSERVED. ON SYDNEY HARBOUR AROUND SAME TIME TWO WATERSPOUTS WERE OBSERVED NEAT ROSE BAY. Severe thunderstorms caused  $20 million damage in Sydney metro area.  3 cm hail and damaging winds were reported. A possible tornado sighting between Kellyville and Chatswood, and waterspouts were observed on Sydney Harbour.

400 to 500 kg tree completely stripped and thrown 150 m. Sheds completely demolished, cars and a bus pushed off the road, the bus was rolled over. A sheep was thrown 1 km. Wild-life killed. A 2 ton cattle feeder was thrown 300 yards uphill.  The funnel cloud was black in colour. Tornado reported at 0430 UTC on 25/11/94 10 to 15 km east of Condobolin.
Cobar hit with tornado and large hail.

O'Brien calls it a 'willy willy'. Steve Malley from Canberra Met Office obseved the tornado also. O'Brien writes "a band of uintense but brief rain and wind squalls crossed the region...at about 2145 [LT] rain and strong gusty E to SE developed to 60 km/hr. By 2000 [LT] the wind veered rapidly through 180 degrees with equally strong W/NW winds." Tornado in Canberra 28th January 1995
4.2 cm hail near Kangaloon at 0545 utc on 15/12/95.
No damage reported. Tornado sighting about 20 km east of Moree at 0150 UTC 0n 20/11/95.  No damage reported.
TRACTORS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN, ROOFS OFF SHEDS AND HOMES. Wind gusts and 4.2 cm hail at Coolamon. A tornado and 4.2 cm hail 5 km south of Rosewood at around 0500 UTC on 30/11/95.
Tornado at Bearbung near Gilgandra at 0330UTC on 29/9/96. Destroyed trees and fences, moved cars 200m, moved a full silo off foundations, unroofed a house.

Ironbark trees 600mm dia broken and pulled out of ground, destroyed a house and several sheds. Extensive damage to fences, moved a 4 tonne truck several lengths. Loud roaring noise heard as well as a deep humming sound. Tornado with 4 cm hail at Elong Elong at 0330 UTC on 29/9/1996. Tornado also reported from Bearbung near Gilgandra and 4 cm hail was reported from Eumungerie.
Woolshed and other buildings damaged. Trees felled. Tornado at Bundella at 0600 UTC on 29/9/1996.

39 caravans overturned or damaged at local caravan park (6 destroyed), 26 units damaged in retirement village, 11 homes suffered roof damage. Tornado (F1) with gusts to 65 kt reported from Fingal Bay at 1800 UTC on  30/6/1998.

One large 4wd rolled over another car ended up ontop of another. A weatherboard house was severely damaged. A baby was sucked out of the house but fortunately was uninjured. Tornado ranked F2 reported from Swinging Ridges Rd (12 km SW of Willow Tree) at 0930 UTC on 27/7/1998.

3 tornado tracks were observed during damage survey. A tornadic thunderstorm moved through the Sydney Metropolitan Area over the afternoon/early evening of 3/11/2000. Around 300 jobs were attended to by SES

Several homes lost roofs, whole (large) trees uprooted and other very localised damage reported. Tornado as well as 6cm hail reported from Uki (E side of Mt Warning) at 0625 UTC on 5/11/2000. Another tornado earlier at Nimbin at 0540 UTC on 5/11/2000.

40 foot palms thrown, goods blown out of house. Accompanied by shriek, 4-6cm hail and toad fall. Narrow swathe. Tornado as well as 6cm hail reported from Uki (E side of Mt Warning) at 0625 UTC on 5/11/2000. Another tornado earlier at Nimbin at 0540 UTC on 5/11/2000.
Time uncertain - inferred from radar. Tornado (F0) at Careel Bay (near Avalon) at about 0235UTC on 18/11/2001.
Tornado lifted garden shed at Leppington (Sydney) at 0500UTC on 18/11/2001.
Tornado overturned moored yachts at Cronulla at 0515UTC on 18/11/2001.
Tornado seen by spotter just west of Moree at 0915UTC on 02/02/2002.

Tornado 100 metres wide lifted hayshed, sucked water from river and uprooted trees 1.5 metres (5 feet) in diameter. On the 7/2/02 at 4:00UTC, near Ebor an 100m wide tornado was spotted travelling in an Easterly direction.  Uprooted large trees, hayshed and water from Serpentine River. (Time uncertain - 0240UTC looks more likely on radar]

Tornado seen to pick up 4WD motorcycle. Was travelling west. Comments: Jimmy Deguara reported a tornado on the ground with debris swirl. The tornado was stationary and growing larger into a large cone. Debris hit a substation. The event was captured on film. A left moving supercell moved NE through the Northen Rivers towards Lismore during the afternoon. The cell weakened slightly as it came into Lismore city, but just as it was past Lismore it interacted with some weaker cells moving towards the SW with the general flow. This generated a tornado that impacted on the town of Dunoon. The SES received 116 RFA's for this event, damage was initially estimated to be in excess of $2 million, and the area was declared a natural disaster zone.

Possible tornado near Toowoomba around 4:15pm AEST. Eight buildings were damaged during the event, though no images or specific details on the damage available. 04-12-1976.

Possible tornado at Gayndah around 6pm AEST. Reports of ten buildings damaged (three demolished), though no images or specific details on the damage available. A heavy metal cattle feeder found more than a kilometre away on a neighbouring property. 01-12-1978.
Possible tornado at Benowa around 9:30am AEST. Reports of stables unroofed. 14-12-1978.

No additional comments or images around this event. 15-12-1980. Widespread thunderstorms in Southeast District late in afternoon with heavy rain and hail reported. Possible tornado at Mungar around 3:40pm AEST. Reports of at least five injuries,fifteen houses damaged between Maryborough and Point Vernon (some partly unroofed) and seven huts either blown down or damaged during the thunderstorm event. 01-06-1981. Thunderstorm reported in the Maryborough area in late afternoon, property damage from strong winds reported from Mungar Junction ; 3 homes and 7 huts either blown down or damaged. Tornado observed at Coolum around 5pm AEST. Widespread thunderstorms over southeast Qld with hail and strong winds. Property damage between Caloundra and Noosa estimated at $1 million. Thunderstorms reported at Warwick 0015 utc, at Brisbane 0115 and 0400 utc, at Archerfield 0315 utc, at Oakey from 0300 utc, at Coolangatta 0545 utc. (C Kotterer Diary)

Tornado observed at Mudgeeraba around 6am AEST. Reports of two buildings damaged, though no pictures or specific details of the damage available. Heavy rain also occurred, which lead to localised flooding. 19-03-1983. Severe thunderstorm event listed in John Butler's Database.

Possible tornado at Cotton Tree Beach around 1:30am AEST. Reports of one death and seven injured. Tornadoes observed ober Moreton Bay around 3pm AEST. One tornado alledgedley came ashore and caused property damage in Redcliffe and Margate, including two houses unroofed, twenty other houses damaged and a trawler sunk at Redcliffe. NULL

Tornado sighted at Daisy Hill around 4pm AEST. Reports of  extensive property damage between Ipswich and the southern suburbs of Brisbane, including 1000 houses damaged, some damage to caravans, trees blown over and power blackouts. Possible tornado at Emu Park (exact time of the event is unknown). Reports of damage to five buildings, though no images or specific details on the damage available. NULL

Tornado observed in Redcliffe around 1pm AEST. Reports of a large amount of damage at Clontarf and near the Redcliffe Aero Club. Damage bill of approximately $10 million. Two deaths were associated with the thunderstorm, including one that drowned as the boat she was in overturned and the other touched a live fallen wire. A yacht at Newport Marina recorded winds of 100 knots before failing. During the event there were 500 homes unroofed, 1000 damaged and 12 strucurally unsafe. Light planes at Redcliffe Airport were flipped over. There were images of corrugated iron almost two-thirds of the way thorugh a palm tree at Clontarf. 24-12-1989. Severe Thunderstorm developed to the south of Warwick and moved NNE up the coast and through Brisbane and the northern bayside suburbs.  Damage in its path between Ipswich and Redcliffe, with the worst affected area being Redcliffe where it is believed a tornado contributed to $10 million worth of damage.  The thunderstorm claimed two deaths.  One drowned as the boat she was in overturned, the other touched a live fallen wire.

Possible tornado at Oakhurst around 2:40pm AEST. Reports of a discontinuous path of destruction through sparsely populated country with one brick house completely destroyed and several others suffered roof damage.  Windows were smashed by hail up to golf ball in size. Three cattle were destroyed after sustaining injury from flying debris.  Large area of pine plantation flattened.Tornado left a discontinuous path of destruction through sparsely populated country. One brick house was completely destroyed. Three cattle were destroyed after sustaining injury from flying debris. Large area of pine plantation flattened. 29-11-1992. Severe thundersorm day across southeast Queensland. A cell developed to the southwest of Maryborough during the early afternoon. The cell then split with a left mover and right mover resulting. The right mover is not reported to have produced any damage. However the left mover moved northeast towards Maryborough, generated a tornado in the unpopulated area of Oakhurst, leaving a discontinuous path of destruction in its wake. One brick house was completely destroyed and several others suffered roof damage. Windows were smashed by hail up to golf ball in size. 3 cattle had to be destroyed due to injury sustained by flying debris. Hundred of acres of pine forest were flattened in the wake of the tornado. 29-11-1992. Severe thundersorm day across southeast Queensland. Tornado observed in the Bucca and Kolan area around 3:30pm AEST. Reports of extensive property and flora damage, including nine houses that were extensively damaged or destroyed. 20 cattle were killed or had to be destroyed. An eyewitness account noted stones embedded in trees, 16-20cm saplings approximately 4-5m long driven through 5 walls of houses, picture fram embedded in opposite wall, fridge missing weeks later and 3 tonne truck body blown or carried 300 metres. 29-11-1992. Widespread severe thunderstorm activity over southeast Queensland.  Severe thunderstorm through Bucca with associated tornado. Caused extensive wind and hail damage.

Possible tornado in parts of Hervey Bay around 1am AEST. Reports of several buildings and caravans damaged during the event. The Pialba caravan park was heavily impacted with two caravans tipped on their side and an annex alledgedly ripped to shreds. 5 people from the caravan park were taken to hospital. Extensive damage sustained to some homes and businesses in Point Vernon and Scarness, including the collapse of a 30 x 5 metre section of brick side wall of a boys department store in Main Street and numerous reports of partial roof loss. No images of the damage were available for assessment and therefore confidence in the assigned Fujita number is not high (could be greater). 21-01-1995. AT APROXIMATELY 1AM ON THE MORNING OF 21 JANUARY 1995 AN EVENT DESCRIBED LOCALLY AS A MINI CYCLONE CAUSED STRUCTURAL AND TREE DAMAGE IN THE VICINITY OF THE PIALBA CARAVAN PARK.  THIS EVENT DOES NOT SEEM TO BE A SEVERE THUNDERSTORM AND NO DEFINITE CAUSE CAN BE DEDUCED FROM THE EYEWITNESS OR DAMAGE DESCRITIONS. ONE POSSIBILITY IS DAMAGE FROM A LANDFALLING WATERSPOUT WHILE ANOTHER IS THE PRESENCE OF A MICROBURST IN THE AREA. THE FOLLOWING ACCOUNT IS FROM THE MARYBOROUGH CHRONICLE OF 23/01/95. FIERCE WINDS RIPPED THROUGH ISOLATED SECTIONS OF HERVEY BAY EARLY ON SATURDAY MORNING LEAVING FIVE PEOPLE INJURED AND SEVERAL BUILDINGS AND CARAVANS DAMAGED. A SPOKESMAN FOR HERVEY BAY POLICE,SERGENT STEVE IMHOFF, SAID THE MINI-CYCLONE SWEPT THROUGH HERVEY BAY ABOUT 1AM CAUSING EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO HOUSES BUSINESS PREMISES AND CARAVANS. ONE OF THE WORST HIT AREAS OF THE BAY WAS PIALBA CARAVAN PARK. FIVE PEOPLE FROM THE PARK WERE TAKEN TO HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT FOLLOWING INJURIES SUSTAINED FROM THE BRIEF STORM. ONE WOMAN WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE MARYBOROUGH BASE HOSPITAL WITH SUSPECTED SPLEEN DAMAGE. A SIX YEAR OLD BRISBANE BOY, TERRY HESSEY RECIEVED SIX STICHES TO HIS FACE AFTER BEING INJURED WHEN HE WAS THROWN FROM ONE END OF HIS CARAVAN TO THE OTHER . HIS FATHER , BRIAN HESSEY , SAID THE FAMILY WAS AWOKEN IN THE EARLY HOURS OF SATURDAY MORNING WHEN GALE FORCE WINDS ROCKED THEIR CARAVAN. MR HESSEY SAID HE MANAGED TO CATCH HIS SON WHEN HE WAS CATPULTED FROM HIS BED AS THE VAN WAS BLOWN ON ITS SIDE. HIS WIFE PATRICIA SAID NEIGHBOURS HAD TO FREE THE FAMILY FROM THE VAN AFTER IT HAD BLOWN OVER IN THE STORM.  THE PEOPLE IN NEIGHBOURING CARAVANS CAME OUT  TO HELP AS SOON AS THEY HEARD THE NOISE. THEY HAD TO WRENCH THE DOOR OPEN SO WE COULD CLIMB OUT. IT WAS SO DISTRESSING
Column1: ESPECIALLY WITH THE WIND AND RAIN AND IT WAS DARK AND WE WERE SO DISORIENTATED
Column2: PATRICIA SAID . ANOTHER FAMILY STAYING AT THE CARAVAN PARK HAD A LUCKY ESCAPE  WHEN THEIR CARAVAN WAS EXTENSIVE DAMAGED BY THE STORM. RON WEST AND HIS FAMILY WOKE TO THE SOUND OF THEIR ANNEX BEING RIPPED TO SHREDS BY THE FIERCE WINDS. SHERON HERVEY, THE WESTS DAUGHTER WAS STAYING IN  THE ANNEX OF THE VAN. SHE AWOKE WHEN THE BRANCH OF A TREE FELL THROUGH THE ANNEX AND LANDED ON HER. SPOKESMAN FOR HERVEY BAY AMBULANCE, GRAHAM COOPER , SAID MOST OF THE INJURIES SUSTAINED DURING THE STORM WERE CUT AND ABRASIONS. ONE WOMAN  WAS TAKEN TO HERVEY BAY HOSPITAL SUFFERING SHOCK. STATE EMERGENCY SERVICE SERVICES CONTROLLER COL PIERCE,SAID THE STORM WAS LIKE A MINI-TORNADO. IT WAS LIKE THE WATER SPOUTS WE EXPERIENCED RECENTLY EXCEPT IT WAS OVER LAND. THAT'S WHY THE DAMAGE SEEMS TO HAVE OCCURRED IN AREAS COVERING ABOUT 50 SQUARE FEET AT A TIME. MR PEARCE SAID THE STORM BROUGHT "FEROCIOUS" WINDS
Column3: BUT DAMAGE WAS SUSTAINED IN ISOLATED AREAS. "WE WERE CALLED OUT TO THREE HOUSES IN POINT VERNON AND ONE IN SCARNESS WHICH HAD ALL SUSTAINED EXTENSIVE ROOF DAMAGE. THE POLES IN THE ROOF HAD ALL BEEN TORN OFF AND DUMPED NEARBY
Column4: AND YET NEIGHOURING HOUSES HARDLY HAD ENOUGH WIND TO STIR PAPER."  MR PEARCE SAID THE DAMAGED HOUSES WERE IN DIAMOND COURT
Column5: APLIN STREET AND BELL STREET POINT VERNON
Column6: AND FRESHWATER STREET SCARNESSS. BUSINESS PREMISES IN TORQUAY ROAD AND  MAIN STREET PIALBA
Column7: WERE SELECTIVELY TARGETED BY THE WHIRLWIND. THE MOST EXTENSIVE DAMAGE WAS SUSTAINED BY BOYS FAMILY DEPARTMENT STORE IN MAIN STREET. A 30M BY 5 M SECTION OF BRICK WALL  AT THE SIDE OF THE BUILDING COLLAPSED DURING THE HEIGHT OF THE STORM
Column8: AND THE ROOF WAS ALSO DAMAGED. PART OF THE ROOF OF A NEIGHBOURING STORE WAS AALSO BLOWN OFF IN THE GALE.  AT  ST JOHNS GARDENS IN TORQUAY ROAD
Column9: SAY IT WITH FLOWERS LOST PART OF ITS ROOF. ACROSS THE ROAD DAVID'S  ULTRASOUND SUFFERED CEILING DAMAGE WHEN PART OF ITS ROOF WAS BLOWN AWAY. THE SUNSEEKER MOTEL AT SCARNESS ALSO HAD EXTENSIVE ROOF DAMAGE. MR  PEARCE SAID ALTHOUGH MUCH OF THE STORM IN ISOLATED POCKETS
Column10: THERE WAS SUBSTANTIAL DAMAGE TO SIGNS AND WINDOWS THROUGHT THE AREA."

Comments: Possible tornado at Cedar Pocket around 4:30pm AEST. Report of swirling debris lifted approximately 300 feet in the air and a very badly damaged timber house. Storm Spotter reported that tree damage in the area suggested a tornado occurred. 08-11-1999.  Approx 06:30utc. Timber house at Cedar Pocket (approx. 6 km east of Gympie) very badly damaged by winds associated with a thunderstorm. Witnesses described swirling debris lifted 300ft into the air, although no funnel was sighted. These witnesses stated   a friend reported a V-shaped funnel cloud on the outskirts of Gympie." Tornado observed near Bethania around 5pm AEST. Report from eyewitness included severe damage to outbuildings, some damage to a house. Kennels, pergola and a shed were destroyed. Some big roof beams were found over 400 metres away. Other damage in the area included brick stable blocks levelled and houses unroofed. Many trees were damaged and large ones uprooted. No images of the damage were available, so the Fujita number was limited to F1. 10/12/99: Storm chasers reported a swathe of property and tree damage stretching from just south of Boonah to Redland Bay, due to strong winds associated with a  thunderstorm. Storm spotter and newspaper reports of large hail. { 5 cm at Brunswick Heads (NSW); 2---3 cm at Stephens (Gold Coast);  Golfball size at Park Ridge, Shailer Park and other areas south of Brisbane. [2 separate cells]

Possible tornado at Rockhampton around 2:30pm AEST. Reports of up to 5 tornadoes in the Rockhampton area, though unable to confirm the occurance of all of these. Estimated damage bill over $200,000 with widespread tree damage and roofing damage to some houses. Reports of a large truck alledgedly being lifted and thrown about 50 metres and images of a large uprooted tree that was lifted onto the roof of a house. Golfball sized hail reported in the outer suburbs of Rockhampton. A 78km/h wind gust was recorded at the Rockhampton Airport Automatic Weather Station.  02/11/2000: Severe storm tore a path of destruction through North Rockhampton suburbs with reports of up to 5 tornadoes (evidence of at least 1 confirmed by the Bureau). Estimated damage bill over $200,000 with widespread tree damage and roofing damage to some houses. Golfball sized hail reported in the outer suburbs with wind estimates to 80kts but only 42kts actually measured at the Rockhampton airport. A large truck was lifted and thrown about 50m.
Tornado observed approximately 35 kilometres southwest of Longreach (along Jundah Road) around 6:30pm AEST. No damage reported. Tornado sighted 35km southwest of Longreach.

Comments: Thunderstorm with marble size hail. Great devastation over a strip of timbered country. Many gums, some over 100 years old, uprooted while others 2 feet in diameter were broken. A number of outbuildings were unroofed. Adelaide; several short sharp thunderstorms with hail, rain and violent gusty winds over the plains and hills. A little after 7am, two rows of big gums on Woodville Rd at Woodville were considerably damaged with huge limbs torn away and hurled across the road. Tramshed and some other buildings unroofed at Brighton.  Tornado likely at Coromandel Valley at 7pm.  Thunderstorms at Verdun (Grunthal) and Mt Barker resulted in heavy hail showers size generally the size of marbles, but in Verdun many windows were broken and other damage done.

funnel cloud observed, stables unroofed at one farm. A house was unroofed on a second farm.  Time only given as afternoon.  A second report mentions a whirlwind. Comments: Immense damage. Path width 100 to 200 at time of most intense damage where practically everything in its path was levelled. It broadened to about 500m before lifting off the ground as it passed over a house, then grounded again snapping off large trees (diameter of 50-60cm) and carrying them up to 20m. Traffic was completely blocked on some roads for some time because of fallen timber. Meadows; severe windstorm and heavy hail. Funnel cloud observed. Path width of immense" damage about 100 to 200m mentioned. Thunderstorm assumed. No other damage or storms mentioned on the day. Time not recorded but morning mentioned."

Gaol lost its roof which was blown over a neighbouring house. Myall trees 40 to 50 ft high were torn out of the ground and in some cases carried 50 yards. Several buildings were extensively damaged during the storm which lasted 10 to 15 minutes. Iron Knob; a storm "more in the nature of a typhoon or tornado". Wind uprooted trees in all directions. The storm extended for only one mile (1600 metres) in width and could be easily traced by the fallen trees.  Described as a cyclone. Time not recorded. The storm extended for only one mile (1600 metres) in width and could be easily traced by the fallen trees.  Described as a cyclone. Time not recorded. Afternoon mentioned.
The track of the storm looked like some mighty roller had passed along

At Wild Dog Hill (just north of Port Wakefield) significant damage inflicted on a house and outhouse and many trees uprooted.     Time given as evening. Comments: On a property near Burra; 2 tornados; trees uprooted, stripped or broken in the centre. A heavy trolly was carried some distance. All sheds and outhouses were unroofed, several windmills blown over. One tornado passed over the dam, carried water about 50 feet into the air, and as a result the gauge showed a depth of at least 2 feet less than immediately before the storm. Cost of damage about 1,000 pounds. Time not recorded. Severe hail and thunderstorms occurred over parts of central and northern agricultural areas of the state; crops, vineyards and orchards were much damaged. Localities include Alford and Wallaroo (YP), Riverton, Marrabel (24mm in 20 minutes), Gulnare and Burra (MN). Near Burra 2 tornados caused much destruction.  Time not recorded but a severe thunderstorm reported in Adelaide at 1:30pm.

A destructive whirlwind caused damage to land which it crossed. Yankalilla; hail the size of pigeon eggs. A whirlwind was mentioned. (possible funnel cloud)  Damage caused to land which the whirlwind crossed.

a violent cyclone, lasting only a few minutes, wrought considerable damage. North Walkerville and Nailsworth; a violent cyclone, lasting only a few minutes, wrought considerable damage. A house in Nailsworth was unroofed and chimney blown down, the roof ended up intact in a paddock 100 yards away. Other houses suffered damage. Stables in North Walkerville were unroofed and fencing levelled.

Many trees uprooted and portions of others torn off. About 1 mile (1600 metres) of telegraph poles were bent about. Electric wires were cut in several places by flying sheets of iron from dwellings. Balaklava; "a cyclone" swept across the counrty and left in its wake torn up trees and damaged sheds and house roofs. Many trees uprooted and portions of others torn off. About 1 mile (1600 metres) of telegraph poles were bent about. Electric wires were cut in several places by flying sheets of iron from dwellings.

a storm described as a destructive willy-willy caused severe damage. houses unroofed, trees and power lines down over narrow path. Short burst of very heavy rain resulted in flooding. Gaugings only around 11mm. All as 1 event because of occurring with a front. Gawler;  just after midnight 5-6 July 1989. Tornado between Gawler east and Sandy Creek.  Most damage between midnight and 1am; Power lines down in Cockatoo Valley, Sandy Creek and Lyndoch and many large trees uprooted in Tanunda Thursday morning. Tailem Bend; Roof off a house about 3 am.
Roxby Downs; fences down and limbs off trees. Narrow path suggests a tornado. Gust to 69 km/h measured.

NPWS officers Heather Kriesl and Trevor Nailsmith witnessed the storm.  Tornado occurrence deduced from description of damage path. 'There was just this incredible roar of wind.  It picked up the red dust and you could not see across the road'.  About 50 trees were felled or damaged, but no damage to the park office or toilets.  The damage path was narrow but at least 3 km long. A likely tornado at Bool Lagoon Conservation Park (LSE);  3 Jan 1991. Tornado occurrence deduced from description of damage path.

Details on damage path are a little vague and contradictory, however, two of three witnesses reported seeing a funnel cloud and all three estimated the wind at about 100 knots. Strong gusty winds, blowing dust and rain were observed with the storm which moved NW to SE.   Damage area to the west and south of Karoonda.  One house on edge of town lost half it's roof;  sheds were unroofed, sheets of corrugated iron blown around and many trees broken or blown over.  600-700 m of fencing 4 km SW of town was flattened.  On a property 15 km south of town, a farm building made of cement bricks was badly damaged. Tornado at Karoonda (ML);  3 Jan 1991. Details on damage path are a little vague and contradictory, however, two of three witnesses reported seeing a funnel cloud and all three estimated the wind at about 100 knots. Strong gusty winds, blowing dust and rain were observed with the storm which moved NW to SE.   Damage area to the west and south of Karoonda.
Long lived tornadic supercell;  22 Jan 1991.  Storm tracked thru Wandearah, Bundaleer Forest,  Jamestown,  Pandappa Station.  See Tech Note for more.
Tornado at Yacka (MN);  22 Jan 1991.  Part of severe thunderstorm outbreak.  See Tech Report for more details.
Tornado at Port Germein (F);  early hours of 23 Jan 1991.  Part of severe thunderstorm outbreak.  See Tech Report for more detail.

10 stobie poles at Carrackalinga snapped off as a waterspout crossed the coast. The steel sections of the poles were rusted. Waterspout moved onshore at Carrickalinga (GAA);  16 June 1991. 10 stobie poles snapped off as a waterspout crossed the coast. The steel sections of the poles were rusted.
Some trees stripped of foliage, many broke off or uprooted. Tornado at Lucindale (LSE);  28 June 1991

Tornado between Mt Torrens and Rockleigh. Damage mostly confined to trees although a shed was involved. Tornado between Mt Torrens and Rockleigh. Severe wind gusts at Adelaide and Parafield (GAA/MLR);  A significant line of showers and thunderstorms passed over Adelaide and the Mt Lofty Ranges and southern Mid North. The Willaston Hotel lost a section of its roof. A roof was blown off in the inner city and billboards destroyed. Large hail reported near Rockleigh.

Some uncertainty as to why this event was classified a tornado.  The storm came from the west or northwest.  The strong gusts lasted about 5 minutes and occurred with rain and small hail.  Sheets of iron were removed from 3 houses;  a home-made carport was destroyed;  about 2 dozen trees were downed in the general area;  Also many tree limbs down.  Damage path was described as narrow, about 1 1/2 km wide.  Heavy rain with the storm - caused bowls to be abandoned! Tornado at Kalangadoo (LSE);  4 April 1992

About 30 large redgums in grazing country had branches torn off.  Limbs of 15-45 cm in diameter were broken off.  Damage was strewn along the damage track, with some debris carried 100-150 metres from the parent tree.  One mature gum was snapped off 4-6 metres above the ground (where trunk was nearly 1 metre in diameter).  Open grazing country to the west of the damaged area.  Photo provided (see file).  Dimensions of damage path provided by the Paltridges. Tornado at Krongart, south southwest of Penola (LSE);  9 June 1992. About 30 large redgums in grazing country had branches torn off.

Details provided by Mrs Barnett.  Path described as 1 1/4 miles long and 80-100 yards wide.  Two trees were uprooted; two were broken off half way up and numerous others had their tops taken off.  Difficult to assess severity.  High F0/low F1. Tornado on farming property, east of Padthaway (USE);  9 June 1992

More than 50 houses were damaged, several suffering major structural damage.  See Fig 2(a) of Met Note 207.  Damage bill estimated as $500,000. Tornado at Salisbury, Adelaide;  12 Aug 1992.  Over 50 houses were damaged over a 4 km track.  See Met Note 207 for more detail.  Several severe convective gusts with front - need to check radar to identify storm cells.

Damage was confined to native vegetation, so monetary loss was minimal.  Damage path about 2 km long, around 50 metres wide and orientated WSW- ENE. Tornado near Auburn (MN);  12 Aug 1992.  See Met Note for more detail.

Graphic photo of the tornado provided by Wayne McCallum.  No details on track length or width.  While there was a lot of hail damage, have not been able to locate any wind damage in the area.  Country is cropped farmland with few trees and widely spaced houses. Long lived supercell spawned tornado near Wirrabara and produced a swathe of large hail from Wirrabara to Appila to Jamestown;  20 Nov 1992. Wirrabara; several trees down near the police station made it impossible to get the car out. Crops damaged by flooding and very strong winds. Jamestown; 5 houses flooded about 5:30pm.

Time uncertain. Tornado at Penfield, Adelaide;  20 Nov 1992. Time uncertain, thought to be about 4:30pm. In the Salisbury area; roof lifted from a shed (riveted on) and 1 pine tree uprooted while 2 others were snapped off. Large hail at Nairne at 4:45pm possibly the same storm. Note a gust at Edinburgh 030 47kt at 3:20pm but this was associated with a period of strong NE winds probably before the tornado.

Tornado damage was surveyed on 21 Sept.  The affected area was mostly cleared grazing land with some vineyards along the western side of Long Gully Road.  Most of the damage was to large gum trees.  A shearing shed lost it's entire roof and a hay shed part of it's roof.  One sheet of roofing iron was found wrapped around a stobie pole.  Another sheet was found 300 metres southeast of the shed impaled on a trellis wire in the vineyard.  The wire had made a 20 cm cut into the iron sheet. Tornado near Angaston;  19 Sept 1993.  Covered with Wind Advice

Tornado cut swathe through the Renmark Golf Course.  15 trees were completely uprooted and numerous others lost limbs.  One golfer described that 'he heard the wind coming'.  No eye-witnesses;  tornado occurrence deduced from damage pattern. Tornado at Renmark (RIV) ;  30 Sept 1993.  Other events on this day - see 50274&5

Narrow swathe of damage on the edge of Barmera; about 3 houses wide and 3 km in length.   Five houses lost part or all of their roofs and over 100 trees were blown (most at the Golf Course).  Need to confirm time with radar. Tornado at Barmera (RIV);  17 Nov 1993

Damage was surveyed by M. Crowe and A. Watson on 26/05/94.  Damage path 650 m long and generally 40-50 m wide, up to 100-120 m wide in parts.  Five buildings suffered significant roof damage;  several fences and trees blown over and telephone lines brought down.  Two lines looked as if they had been cut by flying iron. Tornado at Gawler (GAA);  25 May 1994

J. Pethick surveyed the damage 12/10/94.  A large shearing shed was destroyed and pine tree uprooted at Nangula Springs;  an estimated 500 pine trees at Mt Burr Forest were uprooted, snapped of or badly damaged and 10-15 mature manna gums were damaged on a section of the Overland Track. Tornado near Millicent, including Mt Burr Forest (LSE);  7 Oct 1994

Numerous trees uprooted or stripped.  One new 3m x 3m shed with no floor cemented in, blown about 50 metres to south.  Second new 3m x 3m shed not erected, but stored flat was blown about 25 metres to south.  An old style toilet shed hit by first shed and broken to pieces.  Time of tornado provided by neighbours. Tornado on property, 2 km west of Parndana, (KI);  morning of 25 May 1995.  Covered by a Severe Wind Advice.

About 50 houses were damaged by the tornado.  Twelve houses lost part or all of their roofs and  fifteen others suffered roof damage;  sheds were wrecked or damaged;  trees uprooted and power lines brought down.  No-one was injured.  One estimate put the damage bill at more than $300,000.  The wind was described as lasting 10-15 seconds. Tornado at Gawler (GAA/MLR);  10 June 1995.  Over 50 properties affected, with twelve houses losing all or part of their roofs.

Tornado damage on property belonging to the Hermann family, about 4 km east of Mount Torrens.  Damage to about 12-15 trees, mainly redgums, and to fences which were crushed by falling tree limbs. Storm description provided by property owner (Ian Bidstrip). Area visited briefly by D. Griffiths and J. Pethick several weeks later. Damage path started about 1 km east of Mintaro, and extended SE over 2-2.5 km. The roof of a 100 year old stone building (shearers quarters), including the timbers and ceiling, was torn off. The main section of the roof ended up 300 metres to the southeast. Stoves and fridges in the building were shifted around. Shearers in the building described it going 'deathly quiet', then there was a noise that sounded like a jet engine had started up next door.  They felt it was lucky no-one was killed. Ian said he lost lots of trees as well, some up to 120 years old. Witness estimated time as 1230Z, radar suggests closer to 1245Z. Tornado near Mintaro (MN);  22 Sept 1998. Damage to shearers quarters and trees. Path 50 m wide and 2-2.5 km long. Rated at low end of F1.

Several people witnessed the storm and described seeing a funnel moving quite fast. Damage mapped over a 3 km path, but some sources suggest it may have been up to 8 km long. 4 stobie (power) poles were bent over; 8 large gums with trunks of 1-2 m diametre, were felled; many other trees had limbs broken off; a field bin was lifted over a shed; another field bin blown 250 metres into dam and some roof damage to a house and sheds. Large gums felled, stobie poles bent, field bin lifted over shed, some roof damage to house and sheds. Rated as F1.

Wind had sudden onset and was over very quickly. Tornado deduced from relatively long but narrow damage path. Path about 2 km long, but did appear to be up to 150 metres wide in one area. Tornado damaged sheds, stables and trees at Aldinga (GA&MLR);  17 June 1999.

The damage occurred on farmland and was confined to trees. There were trees around fencelines, roads and along a creek line. Tornado occurrence deduced from narrow damage path. Tornado at Waitpinga, near Victor Harbor (GA&MLR);  18 July 1999. Damage was to trees only and rated as F0.

House unroofed by wind. Iron folded back over the eastern section of the house. Damage very localised. No evidence of damage to adjacent trees or sheds. Stone Hut; Lat/Long  33.10S / 138.30E. House unroofed by wind. Iron folded back over the eastern section of the house. Damage very localised. No evidence of damage to adjacent trees or sheds. Comments: Funnel cloud sighted. No significant damage reports from the area. Bob Beggs reported a tornado at about 6:15 pm near Clarendon.

At least one tornado damaged trees and sheds along a fifteen kilometre path from Sevenhill to near Farrell Flat. Thunderstorms with very heavy rain, wind gusts and some hail affected parts of the state. One long lived severe thunderstorm tracked from northern Yorke Peninsula east-northeast across the Mid North. Very heavy rain caused flash flooding, which forced the closure of several roads, including Highway One north of Port Wakefield (Mid North), and at least one tornado (possibly several) tore limbs off trees and damaged machinery sheds along a fifteen kilometre path from Sevenhill to near Farrell Flat (Mid North).    Heavy rain was reported at Pikes wnes nesar Sevenhill. 27 mm fell in 75 mionutes with 12.5 mm in 15 minutes as the heaviest period. Time around 6 pm.

Moved along a NW-SE path 5/8/98. A short-lived tornado inflicted major structural damage, including removal of the roof, on a house to the north-west of Toodyay (located approximately 75 kilometres to the north-east of Perth). Travelling along a north-west to south-east path the storm also damaged natural vegetation along a trail that measured about 50 metres wide and extended for approximately 1.3 kilometres. The tornado was associated with the passage of an active cold front.

Between Goomalling, Dowerin and Cunderdin. Several buildings were damaged and a swathe was cut through wheat crops 28/8/98. Cut-off low. During the afternoon of the 28th thunderstorms produced severe winds and a tornado in the central wheat belt district between Goomalling (120 kilometres to the north-east of Perth), Dowerin and Cunderdin. Several buildings were damaged and a swathe was cut through wheat crops along a trail that was estimated to be 100 metres wide and 2 kilometres long. Heavy rains and hail (ranging from 7 to 15 mm in diameter) also accompanied the passage of the storms.

400 metres long and 50 metres wide in the Stratton area (north-east suburban Perth). About 2 dozen homes suffered minor damage to roofing, and fences and
garden sheds were blown down. Large branches were blown off trees. Wind gusts during the tornado were estimated to have reached 130 - 150 km/h.

A strong cold front crossed the west coast about 8pm on the evening of the 5th causing widespread damage from Badgingarra to Pemberton. 

Two holiday chalets in Pemberton were damaged by a fallen Karri tree due to the strong winds.

Several homes in Charlwood Morley were damaged, including one which had its windows blown in by wind gusts. Elsewhere, around seven properties were damaged in Merrifield Circle in Leeming.

There was minor damage to properties in Waroona, Mandurah, Harvey, Australind, Bunbury and Pingelly.
